      </div>
      {%- endfor %}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section--alt" id="qb-toxero-compare">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">An honest read</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Where each platform actually wins.</h2>
      <p class="section__lede">Not marketing talking points &mdash; the real differences that matter when you&rsquo;re deciding. The decision is rarely about features; it&rsquo;s about ecosystem, team, and accountant fit.</p>
    </header>
    <div class="vs-scroll">
      <table class="vs-table">
        <caption class="sr-only">QuickBooks Online versus Xero, by capability, from an independent Certified QuickBooks ProAdvisor firm.</caption>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Capability</th>
            <th scope="col">Xero</th>
            <th scope="col" class="vs-table__us">QuickBooks Online</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {%- for row in compare %}
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">{{ row.dim | safe }}</th>
            <td>{{ row.xero | safe }}</td>
            <td class="vs-table__us">{{ row.qb | safe }}</td>
          </tr>
          {%- endfor %}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <div class="stack-8">
      <h3>Where Xero wins</h3>
      <p class="prose">Multi-currency handling is cleaner and sits at a lower price tier. Unlimited users on every plan. The fixed-asset register is native, where QuickBooks needs an add-on. The reconciliation interface is opinionated and many teams prefer it. Bank-feed reliability is comparable, and in some regions slightly better.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="stack-8">
      <h3>Where QuickBooks wins</h3>
      <p class="prose">The U.S. accountant ecosystem is far larger &mdash; Intuit reports more than 700,000 ProAdvisors and accountants. The app marketplace is deeper for U.S. workflows. Built-in payroll is mature and native, where Xero relies on Gusto, ADP, or similar. Inventory and cost-of-goods tracking is native, where Xero leans on paid add-ons. U.S.-centric workflows &mdash; sales tax, 1099s, U.S. banking &mdash; are more native.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="stack-8">
      <h3>Where they&rsquo;re effectively tied</h3>
      <p class="prose">Core double-entry bookkeeping, basic AR/AP, invoicing, expense management, and the mobile apps. For a single-entity U.S. business with standard needs, both platforms do the fundamental job well. The decision is rarely about features &mdash; it&rsquo;s about ecosystem, team, and accountant fit.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

